Wayne, Monday A.M. Jan 28.
Dear Mama: 
At last I've stopped somewhere and things will begin to stand still soon. 
Yesterday I wired Mona about an appointment with Smart, and I am planning to have you meet me at Aurora on Feb. 4th or 5th. I had already written Smart asking him to write to me at Omaha. I'll get there next Saturday, and there'll be plenty of time for him to reply. Then I'll wire you in plenty of time. In the meanwhile you'll be ready. 
I knew at Los Angeles & at Portland that you were especially worried about something. I dreamed both places of you & awoke with an overwhelming source of what your life has been and of your bravery. There was a whole lot more. I saw it all at once & clear as day - the ethos of it, that are too visible in the every humdrum now as to your trouble, I talked with Dr. Long at Tacoma, and he knows a lot, evidently. He told me <del/> that an operation for your trouble is not regarded as an especially serious one. As to cancer, which you fear, he said that people who have a cancer of rapid growth, such as would be the case with you if your fear were <del/> correct, always lose flesh very rapidly. You have not been doing that. As to periodical suffering, that is charactistic of piles in an aggravated stage. The pain comes & goes suddenly. I do not think it's cancer and you should not leap to that conclusion. The symptoms are against it, from what Long told me. Surely a bunch of smaller blood vessels in that place, aggravated by 

